{"summary": "Management practices beneficial for wild bees in temperate forest and grassland ecosystems include several habitat and landscape-level interventions. Reducing the intensity of farmland meadow management through delayed first cutting and reduced agrochemical use can enhance numbers and diversity of wild bees (Action 22). Agri-environment schemes implemented across Europe have shown enhanced diversity and abundance of foraging wild bees relative to conventionally-managed fields, including Swiss Ecological Compensation Areas, German organic arable farming options, Dutch botanical agreements, and Scottish Rural Stewardship Schemes (Action 24). 

Grassland restoration practices show positive results, with species-rich grassland managed under agri-environment schemes attracting more nest-searching queen bumblebees than unmanaged grassland, and restored grasslands developing similar flower-visiting insect communities to ancient species-rich grasslands (Action 8). Field margin management is particularly effective, with uncropped arable field margins sown with native wildflower seed mixes supporting higher abundance and species richness of foraging bumblebees than cropped field edges, grassy margins, or naturally regenerated margins, especially when perennial leguminous herbs are included (Action 19). Naturally regenerated uncropped field margins also support more bumblebees and bee species than cropped margins (Action 20).

Artificial nest site provision shows consistent success, with 29 out of 30 replicated trials across 10 countries demonstrating occupancy by solitary bees, including endangered species, with nest boxes effective within 150-600m of foraging resources (Action 47). Active management of solitary bee populations can increase local populations up to six-fold in one year under good conditions with plentiful floral resources (Action 54). Habitat restoration along watercourses creates sites with similar bee numbers and species to remnant sites, though with different community compositions (Action 1408). Planted flower strips attract more wild bee species and individuals compared to unplanted strips (Action 1406), while hedgerow planting increases bee species in fields and hedgerows themselves, with older hedgerows supporting more species than younger ones (Action 1407).", "action_ids": ["22","24","8","19","20","47","54","1408","1406","1407"], "query": "What are the most beneficial management practices for wild bees in temperate forest and grassland ecosystems?"}

