  "action_title": "Pollination: Plant hedgerows",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nPollination (1 study): One replicated, paired site comparison from the USA\u00a0found higher seed-set in canola plants due to flower visitation by native bees in fields next to planted hedgerows, compared to fields next to unplanted edges. However, this study found no difference in seed-set due to flower visitation by honey bees or syrphid flies.\nCrop visitation (2 studies): One replicated, paired, site comparison from the USA\u00a0found higher crop visitation rates by native bees, but not by honey bees or syrphid flies, in fields next to planted hedgerows, compared to fields next to unplanted edges. Another replicated, paired, site comparison from the USA\u00a0found no difference in flower visitation rates by bees in fields next to planted edges.\nPollinator numbers (6 studies): Five replicated studies from the USA\u00a0found more bee species in fields with hedgerows, or in hedgerows themselves, compared to fields or field edges without hedgerows. Three of these studies\u00a0found more syrphid fly species in hedgerows, compared to field edges without hedgerows. One of these studies\u00a0found similar numbers of syrphid fly species in fields with or without hedgerows. Two of these studies found more native bee and hoverfly individuals\u00a0or more specialist bees in hedgerows, compared to field edges without hedgerows. One replicated site comparison from the USA\u00a0found fewer ground-nesting bees, but similar numbers of bee species and flower-visiting bees, in planted hedgerows, compared to unplanted edges.\nImplementation options (3 studies): Two replicated site comparisons from the USA\u00a0found more bee species in old hedgerows, compared to young hedgerows, and one of these studies\u00a0also found more syrphid fly species. One replicated site comparison from the USA\u00a0found more bee species on native plants, compared to non-native plants, in old hedgerows, but not in young hedgerows."
}

tools_called.args:
{"query": "Beyond on-farm habitat creation, what alternative actions in other landscapes have been tested to benefit bees?", "summary": "Alternative actions in non-farm landscapes that have been tested to benefit bees include several approaches across different habitat types. Road verges have been a significant focus area, with studies showing that restoring species-rich grassland on road verges using native prairie vegetation supported greater numbers and diversity of bees than frequently mown grassed verges (Action 30). Along road and railway verges, restored roadside prairies and verges sown with native wildflowers had higher species richness and diversity of pollinators than verges dominated by non-native vegetation (Action 3854). Altering mowing regimes on greenspaces and road verges also showed benefits, with less frequently mown or unmown urban greenspaces having higher species richness and diversity of butterflies and moths than more frequently mown areas (Action 3841). 

Urban environments offer additional opportunities through planting parks, gardens and road verges with appropriate native species, which showed greater species richness of butterfly and moth adults and caterpillars compared to areas with mixed or exclusively non-native plant species (Action 3842). Green infrastructure in urban areas such as green roofs had lower abundance of butterflies than urban parks, but abundance was higher on older green roofs with more nectar plant species in larger areas (Action 3837). Wildlife gardening practices in urban settings showed mixed results, with gardens where insecticides and herbicides were not used having higher abundance of butterflies (Action 3834, 3900).

Hedgerow planting provided benefits with more bee species found in fields with hedgerows or in hedgerows themselves compared to fields or field edges without hedgerows, and higher crop visitation rates by native bees in fields next to planted hedgerows (Action 1407). Habitat restoration along watercourses showed similar numbers of bees and bee species in restored versus remnant sites, though with different bee communities (Action 1408). Additionally, stopping herbicide use on pavements and road verges resulted in greater species richness and abundance of butterflies in restored roadside prairies compared to areas with unrestricted herbicide application (Action 3899). Commercial rearing and management of solitary bee populations has also been tested, particularly for Megachilidae species, with local populations able to increase up to six-fold in one year under good management conditions with plentiful floral resources (Action 54).", "action_ids": ["30","3854","3841","3842","3837","3834","3900","1407","1408","3899","54"]}

