{"query": "What interventions are available to improve nesting habitat for ground-nesting bees?", "summary": "The primary intervention for improving nesting habitat for ground-nesting bees is creating patches of bare ground. One replicated controlled trial in Germany and four small trials have shown that artificially exposed areas of bare soil can be successfully colonised by ground-nesting solitary bees and wasps in the first or second year (Action ID: 13). However, evidence for the effect of creating areas of bare ground on bee populations or communities on a larger scale has not been captured.

Tillage management shows mixed results for ground-nesting bees. Evidence on whether reduced tillage or no tillage benefits ground-nesting bees is mixed, with two replicated trials on squash farms in the USA having contrasting results - one showed no difference in bee abundance between tilled and untilled farms, while the other found three times more squash bees on no-till farms than on conventional farms (Action ID: 11).

For some ground-nesting species, artificial nest sites may be relevant. A small trial tested three soil-filled nest boxes for the mining bee Andrena flavipes in the UK, but they were not occupied (Action ID: 47). This suggests that while artificial nesting structures work well for cavity-nesting solitary bees, soil-filled boxes may not be effective for ground-nesting species.", "action_ids": ["13","11","47"]}

