{
  "query": "What are the documented effects of reducing the intensity of farming practices, such as tillage, grazing, and meadow management, on wild bee populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Documented evidence on the effects of reducing farming intensity on wild bee populations shows mixed but generally positive results. Regarding meadow management, four replicated trials in Europe compared extensively managed farmland meadows with conventionally farmed meadows or silage fields, with two finding enhanced numbers and diversity of wild bees on meadows with delayed first cut and little agrochemical use, while two found no difference in bee diversity or abundance between conventional meadows and meadows with reduced fertilizer use or cutting intensity (Action 22). For tillage practices, evidence is mixed with two replicated trials on squash farms in the USA showing contrasting results - one found no difference in bee abundance between tilled and untilled farms, while the other found three times more squash bees on no-till farms than on conventional farms (Action 11). Regarding organic farming as a form of reduced intensity, three replicated trials in Europe or Canada showed higher wild bee abundance under organic arable farming than conventional farming, with one showing higher bee diversity in organically farmed wheat fields, though three other replicated trials found no significant difference in bumblebee numbers, species, or wild bees visiting flowering crops between conventional and organic farms (Action 25). For agri-environment schemes that typically involve reduced farming intensity, four replicated trials in Europe showed enhanced diversity and/or abundance of foraging wild bees on land managed under various schemes relative to conventionally-managed fields, while four other trials found no enhancement in bee numbers or species under agri-environment schemes (Action 24).",
